No problem at all! Let’s figure this out together.

Key Idea:

The else  block is optional—it depends on what you want your program to do when the

number is not positive (negative or zero).

Option 1: Skip else  (Do Nothing for Non-Positive Numbers)

If you omit the else , the program will simply ignore non-positive numbers:

c

if (number > 0) {

// Calculate and print square/square root

printf("Square: %f\n", number * number);

printf("Square root: %f\n", sqrt(number));

}

// Program continues silently if number <= 0

Use this if: The exercise only requires action for positive numbers.

Option 2: Add else  with a Message (No return 0 )

If you want to notify the user but keep the program running:

c

if (number > 0) {

printf("Square: %f\n", number * number);

printf("Square root: %f\n", sqrt(number));

}

else {

printf("Please enter a positive number next time!\n");

}

Use this if: You want to give feedback but not exit the program.

Option 3: Add else  with return 0  (Exit Early)

If the program should stop immediately for non-positive numbers:

c

if (number > 0) {

printf("Square: %f\n", number * number);

printf("Square root: %f\n", sqrt(number));

}

else {

printf("Invalid input. Program stopped.\n");

return 0;  // Exits the program

}

Use this if: The program has no reason to continue after a bad input.

Which One Should You Use?

For beginners, Option 2 (message without return 0 ) is often clearest—it teaches

feedback without abrupt exits.

If you’re writing a function that must have a positive number, Option 3 makes sense.

