No problem at all! Let's break it down step by step. I'll show you how to modify the code

to find the maximum value in the matrix, and then we'll make it work for any size ( N x M

).

Part 1: Finding the Maximum (Instead of Minimum)

To find the maximum value, we only need to change two things from the minimum-

finding code:

1. Initialize max  with matrix[0][0]  (same as before).

2. Change the comparison from <  to >  (now looking for larger values).

Modified Code for Maximum

c

int max = matrix[0][0];  // Start with the first element

for (int i = 0; i < 3; i++) {

for (int j = 0; j < 3; j++) {

if (matrix[i][j] > max) {  // Changed from `<` to `>`

max = matrix[i][j];     // Update if current element is larger

}

}

}

printf("The maximum value is: %d\n", max);

Key Difference:

Before: if (matrix[i][j] < min)  → Finds smallest.

Now: if (matrix[i][j] > max)  → Finds largest.

Part 2: Making It Work for Any Size ( N x M )

To handle a matrix of user-defined size, we need to:

1. Ask the user for rows  ( N ) and columns  ( M ).

2. Use these values in the loops instead of hardcoding 3 .

Full Flexible Code

c

#include <stdio.h>

int main() {

int rows, cols;

// Get matrix size from user

printf("Enter number of rows: ");

scanf("%d", &rows);

printf("Enter number of columns: ");

scanf("%d", &cols);

int matrix[rows][cols];  // Declare matrix after knowing size

// Input matrix elements

printf("Enter matrix elements:\n");

for (int i = 0; i < rows; i++) {

for (int j = 0; j < cols; j++) {

scanf("%d", &matrix[i][j]);

}

}

// Find maximum

int max = matrix[0][0];

for (int i = 0; i < rows; i++) {

for (int j = 0; j < cols; j++) {

if (matrix[i][j] > max) {

max = matrix[i][j];

}

}

}

printf("Maximum value: %d\n", max);

return 0;

}

Key Changes:

1. rows  and cols  are now variables (not fixed at 3 ).

2. Loops run up to rows  and cols  instead of 3 .

