Great! Let's put everything together in a complete, corrected program with clear

explanations.

Complete Corrected Program

c

#include <stdio.h>

int main() {

int age, current_year, birth_year;

char had_birthday;

// Get user input

printf("Enter your age: ");

scanf("%d", &age);  // & needed here for scanf

printf("Enter the current year: ");

scanf("%d", &current_year);  // & needed here

printf("Have you had your birthday this year? (Y/N): ");

scanf(" %c", &had_birthday);  // Space before %c to skip whitespace

// Calculate birth year

if (had_birthday == 'Y' || had_birthday == 'y') {

birth_year = current_year - age;

} else {

birth_year = current_year - age - 1;

}

// Print result - NO & here!

printf("Your birth year is: %d\n", birth_year);

return 0;

}

Key Points Explained

1. &  in scanf  vs printf

scanf  needs &  because it puts values INTO variables (needs their addresses)

printf  just displays values (doesn't need addresses)

2. The space in " %c"

Cleans up any leftover Enter key presses

Ensures you get the actual 'Y' or 'N' you want

3. Birthday logic

If birthday passed: current_year - age

If not: current_year - age - 1

How to Test It

Try these inputs to verify:

1. Age: 25, Year: 2023, Birthday: Y → 1998

2. Age: 25, Year: 2023, Birthday: N → 1997

3. Age: 0, Year: 2023, Birthday: Y → 2023 (newborn)

Common Mistakes to Avoid

1. Forgetting the space before %c

2. Using &  in printf

3. Mixing up =  (assignment) and ==  (comparison) in the if-statement

