Let’s break down the issues in this code and fix them step by step. I'll guide you through

the corrections while explaining the concepts.

Problem 1: Array Input

Your current scanf  only reads one integer, but you need to read 10 integers into the

array.

How to Fix:

1. Use a loop to read all 10 elements.

2. Ensure each element is stored in nums[i] .

Corrected Input Code:

c

int main() {

int nums[10];

printf("Enter 10 numbers: ");

for(int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {

scanf("%d", &nums[i]);  // Read into each element

}

printf("Sum: %d", sum_array(nums));

return 0;

}

Problem 2: Missing Semicolon

int nums[10]  is missing a semicolon ( ; ).

Fixed:

c

int nums[10];  // Corrected

Problem 3: sum_array() Not Declared

If sum_array()  is defined after main() , the compiler won’t recognize it.

Solution:

1. Declare the function before main()  (prototype).

2. Or define sum_array()  above main() .

Option 1: Function Prototype

c

int sum_array(int array[10]);  // Declaration

int main() {

// ... rest of the code

}

Option 2: Define Before main()

c

int sum_array(int array[10]) {

// ... function body

}

int main() {

// ... rest of the code

}

Final Corrected Code

c

#include <stdio.h>

// Function prototype

int sum_array(int array[10]);

int main() {

int nums[10];

printf("Enter 10 numbers: ");

for(int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {

scanf("%d", &nums[i]);  // Read each number

}

printf("Sum: %d", sum_array(nums));

return 0;

}

// Function definition

int sum_array(int array[10]) {

int sum = 0;

for(int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {

sum += array[i];

}

return sum;

}

Key Lessons Learned

1. Array Input → Use a loop with scanf  to fill an array.

2. Semicolons → Every statement must end with ; .

3. Function Order → Either:

Define functions before main() , or

Declare them first (prototypes).

4. scanf  with Arrays → Use &nums[i]  (address of each element).

