Critical Issue in Your Revised Code

Your new version has a logical flaw. Let’s analyze it:

Problem: Double-Counting the New Largest

c

if (array[i] > largest) {

largest = array[i];

count = 1;

}

if (array[i] == largest) {  // This *always* runs after the first if!

count++;                // So count becomes 2 immediately

}

Example:

For [3, 5, 2] :

At i=1  ( 5 > 3 ):

largest = 5 , count = 1  (correct).

Then, 5 == 5  → count++  → count = 2  (wrong!).

How to Fix It?

1. Option 1: Use else if  (as in the original solution).

This ensures only one block executes per number.

2. Option 2: Merge the conditions:

c

if (array[i] > largest) {

largest = array[i];

count = 1;

} else if (array[i] == largest) {  // Only runs if not > largest

count++;

}

Why Your Version Fails

The second if  runs independently of the first, leading to:

Correctly finding a new largest , but then incorrectly incrementing count  again.

The else if  ensures mutual exclusivity.

Final Corrected Code

c

for (i = 1; i < n; i++) {

if (array[i] > largest) {

largest = array[i];

count = 1;

}

else if (array[i] == largest) {  // Critical: 'else' here!

count++;

}

}

Key Lesson:

Use else if  when conditions are related and mutually exclusive.

Test edge cases (e.g., [5, 5, 1] , [1] , [2, 2, 2] ).

