Not quite! Let’s break down why this approach doesn’t work for summing elements

above the main diagonal.

Problem with Your Approach

1. matrix[i][j] + matrix[i+1][j+1]

This only adds two specific elements at a time (e.g., [0][1] + [1][2] ), but misses

many others (like [0][2] , [0][3] , etc.).

It also risks going out of bounds (e.g., if i=4 , i+1  is invalid).

2. We need to sum all elements where j > i , not just adjacent pairs.

Correct Approach: Nested Loops with Condition

To sum all elements above the diagonal:

1. Use nested loops to traverse every element in the matrix.

2. For each matrix[i][j] , check if j > i .

3. If true, add matrix[i][j]  to sum .

Final Code Structure

c

#include <stdio.h>

int main() {

int matrix[5][5];

int sum = 0;

// Step 1: Read the 5x5 matrix

printf("Enter 25 integers for the 5x5 matrix:\n");

for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {

for (int j = 0; j < 5; j++) {

scanf("%d", &matrix[i][j]);

}

}

// Step 2: Sum elements above the main diagonal

for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {

for (int j = 0; j < 5; j++) {

if (j > i) {  // Condition for above diagonal

sum += matrix[i][j];

}

}

}

// Step 3: Print the result

printf("Sum of elements above the main diagonal: %d\n", sum);

return 0;

}

Key Takeaways

Loop through all elements: Use i  for rows, j  for columns.

Condition j > i : Selects elements strictly above the diagonal.

Add to sum : Use sum += matrix[i][j]  to accumulate values.

